    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Prominence</strong> is one of Google's three core local search ranking factors (alongside relevance and distance). It measures how well-known a business is both online and offline. Online prominence is built through Google reviews, directory citations, backlinks, and web content. Businesses with 50+ reviews significantly outperform those with 5-10 reviews in local pack rankings, according to BrightLocal's Local Search Ranking Factors study.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Google ranking factor</div>
            <div class="tms-value">1 of 3 core factors</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Top signal</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Google Reviews</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Distance is fixed by your address. Relevance is limited by your category and services. Prominence is the one local ranking factor with no ceiling — you can always build more reviews, more citations, more content, more links. It's where long-term local SEO investment pays off.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is prominence in local ranking?</h2>
        <p>Google defines prominence as how well-known a business is in the real world and on the web. It's explicitly stated in Google's local ranking documentation: "Some places are more prominent in the offline world, and search results try to reflect this in local ranking."</p>
        <p>Prominence has two dimensions:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Offline prominence</strong> — the real-world reputation of a business. A nationally recognized hotel chain has inherent offline prominence that a new motel doesn't have, regardless of their digital footprint.</li>
          <li><strong>Online prominence</strong> — what Google can measure algorithmically: review count and rating, citation consistency across directories, backlinks from relevant sites, mentions in local media, and overall web presence including content volume and freshness.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">BrightLocal 2024 Local Search Ranking Factors</div>
          <p>Google reviews consistently rank as the <strong>#1 prominence signal</strong> in practitioner surveys. Businesses showing more reviews and higher ratings perform better in local pack results. Review recency matters too — a business getting reviews monthly outperforms one with the same total count but no recent reviews.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why prominence matters for local rankings</h2>
        <p>Of the three local ranking factors, prominence is the one that compounds with investment. Here's why it matters:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>It's the factor you control.</strong> You can't move your address (distance) and you can't manufacture relevance beyond your actual services. But you can always generate more reviews, build more citations, earn more links, and publish more content.</li>
          <li><strong>Reviews are a direct ranking signal.</strong> Google's algorithm gives explicit weight to review count, average rating, recency, and the content of reviews (keywords in reviews reinforce relevance).</li>
          <li><strong>Citation consistency signals legitimacy.</strong> Consistent NAP (Name, Address, Phone) data across 50+ directories tells Google your business is established and trustworthy. Inconsistent citations create ambiguity that suppresses rankings.</li>
          <li><strong>Web authority compounds.</strong> Each backlink, each article mention, each blog post adds to your prominence score. Unlike a map pin location, these signals accumulate and don't disappear.</li>
          <li><strong>Prominence differentiates in competitive markets.</strong> In dense urban markets where 20 businesses have the same relevance and similar distance to a searcher, prominence is the tiebreaker.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Google measures prominence</h2>
        <p>Google's local algorithm evaluates prominence through several measurable signal categories:</p>

        <h3>Review signals</h3>
        <p>The most heavily weighted prominence factor. Google evaluates:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Review count</strong> — total number of Google reviews. More reviews = stronger signal.</li>
          <li><strong>Average rating</strong> — higher ratings reinforce prominence, but volume matters more than perfection. A 4.7-star business with 200 reviews outranks a 5.0-star business with 12 reviews.</li>
          <li><strong>Recency</strong> — businesses receiving reviews consistently every month signal active, ongoing customer satisfaction. A business that got all its reviews 2 years ago and stopped is weaker than one with the same count spread over time.</li>
          <li><strong>Review content</strong> — keywords in review text (e.g., "best family dentist," "emergency plumber") reinforce the business's relevance for those terms.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Citation signals</h3>
        <p>Citations are mentions of your business NAP data (Name, Address, Phone) across the web — in directories, review sites, local publications, and industry databases. Google cross-references these to verify business legitimacy. Consistent NAP across 50+ authoritative directories is a meaningful prominence signal. Inconsistencies (different phone numbers, old addresses, spelling variations) create ambiguity that weakens the signal.</p>

        <h3>Web authority signals</h3>
        <p>Backlinks from local news sites, regional directories, chambers of commerce, and industry publications directly feed prominence. A plumber mentioned in a "top home services in [city]" roundup benefits from both the citation and the backlink. Regular blog content creates web presence that compounds prominence over time.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Prominence vs relevance vs distance — the three local ranking factors</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
