        <h2 id="examples">Real prominence-building examples</h2>

        <h3>Example 1 — Dental practice</h3>
        <p>A dentist with 230 Google reviews (4.8 average), listings in 45 directories, and 80 published blog articles outranks nearby competitors with higher proximity to searchers. The prominence signals are strong enough to overcome the distance disadvantage in 6 out of 10 relevant local queries. Review volume was built through a systematic post-appointment ask: a printed card with a QR code linking directly to the Google review prompt.</p>

        <h3>Example 2 — Local restaurant entering the local pack</h3>
        <p>A new restaurant broke into the local pack within 6 months through three parallel actions: building citations across 60 directories in the first month, asking every table for a Google review using a QR code tent card, and publishing weekly blog posts about local food culture. Starting from zero reviews, they reached 85 reviews at 4.6 stars within 6 months and overtook competitors with significantly longer track records.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Prominence vs Google Business Profile optimization — which matters more</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Build prominence first when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You have fewer than 25 Google reviews</li>
              <li>Your citation profile has inconsistencies or gaps</li>
              <li>Competitors have 5x more reviews than you</li>
              <li>You're in a market with many similar businesses</li>
              <li>Rankings are stuck despite good GBP setup</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Optimize GBP first when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Your profile is missing category assignments</li>
              <li>Business description doesn't include core keywords</li>
              <li>Photos are missing or outdated</li>
              <li>Services and attributes are incomplete</li>
              <li>Q&amp;A section has unanswered questions</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for building local prominence</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Build a review request system, not a one-off ask.</strong> The businesses with 200+ reviews didn't get there by occasionally asking. They have a repeatable system: post-service email, in-person QR code, or SMS follow-up within 24 hours of service completion.</li>
          <li><strong>Prioritize citation consistency before citation volume.</strong> Fix NAP inconsistencies across existing listings before adding new ones. Google weighs consistent citations over a high count with conflicting data.</li>
          <li><strong>Earn backlinks from local and industry sources.</strong> Sponsor a local event and get a backlink from the event page. Contribute to a local news article. Get listed in your chamber of commerce directory. Local links carry more prominence weight than generic directories.</li>
          <li><strong>Respond to every Google review.</strong> Google has confirmed that responding to reviews shows engagement and may improve prominence. It also demonstrates to prospective customers that you're attentive — which indirectly drives more reviews.</li>
          <li><strong>Publish local content consistently.</strong> A blog publishing 4+ articles per month about local topics (neighborhood guides, local event coverage, community involvement) builds web presence that directly feeds prominence.</li>
          <li><strong>Get listed on data aggregators first.</strong> Neustar Localeze, Data Axle, and Foursquare feed data to hundreds of downstream directories. Getting these right propagates accurate NAP data across the web automatically.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — review gating</div>
          <p>Asking customers to rate their experience before directing them to Google (and only directing happy customers to leave reviews) violates Google's review policies. Google calls this review gating and will remove reviews, and in severe cases, suppress a business listing entirely. Ask every customer for a review — let the ratings reflect your actual service quality.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common prominence mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Buying reviews</strong> — fake reviews violate Google's policies and are increasingly detected and removed, sometimes with listing suspension.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring NAP consistency</strong> — a business with 100 citations but 30% having a different phone number sends a confused signal to Google.</li>
          <li><strong>Only collecting reviews on Google</strong> — Yelp, Facebook, and industry-specific sites also contribute to prominence. Diversify the review profile.</li>
          <li><strong>Letting review velocity drop to zero</strong> — a burst of 50 reviews followed by 6 months of silence signals the business may have closed. Maintain consistent monthly review acquisition.</li>
          <li><strong>No local content strategy</strong> — a website with no local content misses a major web presence signal. Publish locally relevant content consistently.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring review gating policies</strong> — filtering only happy customers to review platforms risks listing suppression.</li>
        </ul>

